Events.html: 1056 – After a sudden illness a few days previously, Byzantine Empress Theodora dies childless, thus ending the Macedonian dynasty.

Events.html: 1422 – King Henry V of England dies of dysentery while in France. His son, Henry VI becomes King of England at the age of 9 months.

Events.html: 1795 – War of the First Coalition: The British capture Trincomalee (present-day Sri Lanka) from the Dutch in order to keep it out of French hands.

Events.html: 1798 – Irish Rebellion of 1798: Irish rebels, with French assistance, establish the short-lived Republic of Connacht.

Events.html: 1803 – Lewis and Clark start their expedition to the west by leaving Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania at 11 in the morning.

Events.html: 1813 – At the final stage of the Peninsular War, British-Portuguese troops capture the town of Donostia (now San Sebastián), resulting in a rampage and eventual destruction of the town. Elsewhere, Spanish troops repel a French attack in the Battle of San Marcial.

Events.html: 1864 – During the American Civil War, Union forces led by General William T. Sherman launch an assault on Atlanta, Georgia.
Events.text: During the American Civil War, Union forces led by General William T. Sherman launch an assault on Atlanta, Georgia.

Events.html: 1876 – Ottoman Sultan Murat V is deposed and succeeded by his brother Abd-ul-Hamid II.

Events.html: 1886 – An earthquake kills 100 in Charleston, South Carolina.
Events.text: An earthquake kills 100 in Charleston, South Carolina.

Events.html: 1888 – Mary Ann Nichols is murdered. She is the first of Jack the Ripper's confirmed victims.
Events.text: Mary Ann Nichols is murdered. She is the first of Jack the Ripper's confirmed victims.

Events.html: 1895 – German Count Ferdinand von Zeppelin patents his Navigable Balloon.

Events.html: 1897 – Thomas Edison patents the Kinetoscope, the first movie projector.

Events.html: 1907 – Count Alexander Izvolsky and Sir Arthur Nicolson sign the St. Petersburg Convention, which results in the Triple Entente alliance.

Events.html: 1920 – Polish-Bolshevik War: a decisive Polish victory in the Battle of Komarów.

Events.html: 1936 – Radio Prague, now the official international broadcasting station of the Czech Republic, goes on the air.

Events.html: 1939 – Nazi Germany mounts a staged attack on the Gleiwitz radio station, creating an excuse to attack Poland the following day thus starting World War II in Europe.
